\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
The use of robots has been proven successful in many cases of subjects with
 different neurodevelopmental disorders, e.g., intellectual disability, attention-
deficit, hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), Autistic Spectrum Disorder (ASD)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WhyRobots"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SocialRobots"

\end_inset

.The use of social robots to provide alternative, “virtual” forms of Pet
 Therapy has been explored in research since late nineties.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Pet Therapy (PT) is a treatment that works well especially with NDD children,
 leading to improvements in various spheres.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

According to current research
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PetTherapy"

\end_inset

, PT helps NDD subjects to release their often persistent state of anxiety
 and improves relaxation, as human-animal bond acts on “stress hormones”
 production, inducing a reduction of arterial pressure, cardiac and respiratory
 rates.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Some studies have found that 5- and 6-year-olds who were more attached to
 their pets expressed more empathy toward peers and that 7- to 10- year-olds
 who had more “intimate talks” with their pets also had more empathy toward
 their peers.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The pioneer in this field is PARO, a stuffed robot shaped like a baby harp
 seal and equipped with five kinds of sensors - tactile, light, audition,
 temperature, and posture sensors - with which it can perceive people and
 its environment.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Paro"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\shape italic

\begin_inset Float figure
